column168: On 8/1/07 at 2045 hrs, Flying J tractor trailer struck another tractor trailer on westbound Rt. 33 in Wheeler IL, causing it to overturn. Vehicle lost approximately 4000 gallons of diesel fuel and caught fire resulting in the death of the driver.  Haz mat team was immediatly called in by Flying J safety department, at which time HMHTTC Response Inc's Chicago office mobilized to the site with 4 responders, 1 vac truck and a frac tank. Sand birms were initially installed to prevent migration of the spill. Vac work started and continued until 1724 hrs on 8/3/2007 with 5,000 gallons of fuel/water recovered, 2,000 gallons of which was diesel fuel. On 8/8/07, HMHTTC crew of 5 with excavator, skid steer and 3 dump trucks returned to site for excavation. Over time frame of 8/8 to 8/10/07, 464 tons of contaminated soil were excavated from area of 200'L X 5-13'W X 5-8'D on the side of the road. 547 tons of backfill were used to restore excavation site. At the request of IEPA, 19 soil samples were also taken during this time and delivered to a certified lab for testing for BTEX and PNA's along with a VOC of nearby well water. Liquid/solids from frac tank and excavation were properly disposed of. HMHTTC crew also powerwashed a small amount of smoke residue from the siding of a nearby house at 1749 E. State Highway 33, Wheeler IL 62479 and replaced 4 cherry trees that were destroyed in the accident. As of 1200 hrs 8/10/07, excavation and restoration of site has been completed.
column169: At this time, still awaiting accident reconstruction report to make recommendations.

column168: The IBC that failed was being transfered from one trailer to another.  An employee was attempting to push the IBC to back of the trailer by placing another IBC in front of it and pushing it with a forklift that was on the ground.  We believe the pressure of being pushed is what caused the IBC to crack.  Material in the IBC was a Waste Corrosive Liquid Spent Acids carrying the following EPA Waste Codes, D002, D006, D007, D008, and D011.  After the rupture occured the drum was then tilted to stop the flow of liquid.  Approximately 60 (sixty) gallons of material was spilled in the trailer and onto the ground.  Absorbent was immediately put down and the spill contained to the property.  Cleanup consisted of using absorbent to stabalize free liquids and a neutrilizer was used to wash down the trailer and pavement.  The cleanup effort created 2 (two) cubic yard boxes of debris.  The remaining material in the tote was transfered into 3 (three) 55-gallon poly UN rated drums.
column169: It is against company policy to use a tote to push another tote.  Employees are provided a pallet jack to use to move drums to the back of a trailer.  Due to the space it is impossible to get a forklift into a trailer to move containers.  Both employees involved were given a verbal warning as it was the first incident for each employee.  All employees have be retrained on proper loading procedures.  We do not forsee this becoming an issue again.

column168: While traveling east on I-10, driver heard a noise that resembled a blowout coming from left rear of trailer.  Driver pulled over and as he approached the rear of the trailer, he heard a tire blow out on the right side and noticed flames coming from the area.  He attempted to put the fire out with his onboard fire extinguisher, but was unsuccessful.  He called 911, woke up his co-driver, and disconnected the tractor from the trailer.  The Fire Department arrived and closed the highway to extinguish the fire.  While the fire was being extinguished, the safety/rupture disc failed due to high pressure and hydrogen released into the atmosphere.  Since the road closure was not a direct result of the hazardous material, we did not make the telephonic report.

column168: GATX 33171 was being unloaded at the consignee's plant when a carrier train crew coupled to a cut of cars including GATX 33171.  The blue flag protection had been removed from the track and the conductor walked the track to within one car length of GATX 33171 before pulling the cut of cars.    The movement of GATX 33171 resulted in damage to the unloading hose and the release of approximately 150 gallons of material into the plant containment system.      The car was re-spotted to complete unloading and all released material was recovered.  There was no damage to the tank car valves or fittings.    Note that GATX 33171 had not been released into transportation in commerce.

column168: During an routing TAG (The Adherence Group) tariff compliance inspection, TAG discovered two cargons of lighters that were labelled but were not listed on the dangerous goods declaration.  The dangerous goods declaration did list other class 2.1, 2.1, 6.1 and class 9 hazardous cargo but the two cartons of lighters were omitted.  The class 6.1 cargo was also a marine pollutant with marine pollutant markings but the marine pollutant designation was not listed on the dangerous goods declaration and the ocean container was not marked "marine pollutant". column42: SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE, SOLUTION, WITH 16 PERCENT OR MORE AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: On August 9th, 2007, at approximately 7:45 p.m. CDT, a tractor-trailer operated by Pro-Fleet, was traveling on 71st Highway, when the subject vehicle suffered a load shift.  As a result of the shift, a 15 gallon container of Sodium hypochlorite (bleach) was punctured and approximately 10 gallons of the 12.5% bleach concentration was released onto the trailer floor.  The bleach subsequently migrated onto the roadway.  At 8:15 p.m. CDT, Mr. Paul Dolak, with Brenntag Mid-South, Inc., retained Cura Emergency Services (CES) to manage the environmental cleanup operations on their behalf.  Mr. Dolak had already dispatched a crew from Hazmat Response, Inc. to the site.  The Kansas City Fire Department had already begun applying soda ash to the impacted areas of the roadway.  The Kansas City Police Department was also on site providing traffic control.  The Hazmat Response, Inc. crew met with on site personnel.  The crew began by applying additional soda ash onto the impacted roadway.  The material was then collected and placed into drums.  Brenntag Mid-South personnel retained custody of the cleanup materials to be bulked with similar materials at their facility.

A van trailer containing hazardous waste was placed at the receiving dock for processing.  Upon inspection of the interior of the trailer it was discovered that a 55 gallon 1A1 steel drum had ruptured allowing approximately 25 gallons of material to be released from the package onto the floor of the van trailer.  Please note material did not escape to the environment as it was fully contained within the trailer.  Upon further inspection, it was discovered that the contents of the drum polymerized causing the top of the drum to fail.  Facility personnel, using appropriate personal protective equipment entered the trailer and recontainerized all released material.  The recovered solidified material, along with the original container was placed in a suitable salvage drum and was disposed of at the facility as this location was the intended waste management facility.  In addition, there were 8 additional 55 gallon containers of the same material included in the shipment.  While these containers displayed no signs of a reaction, they were immediately processed and disposed of.
column169: At the time of loading, the containers were inspected and no sign or indication of a reaction was evident.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper of the material in question will be required to certify that future shipments have been properly inhibited to prevent an unwanted reaction during transportation.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was intransit between the point of origin and the intended waste management facility.  Upon arrival at the intended waste management facility, it was discovered that a container on the vehicle had leaked allowing approximately 1 gallon of material to be released onto the floor of the van trailer and through the floor of the trailer onto the ground.  Facility personnel immediatley donned appropriate protective equipment and initiated appropriate response procedures.  Upon identification of the damaged container, it was determined that a 55 gallon steel drum had been loaded next to the leaking drum, causing a dent which developed a pinhole leak.  During transportation, the load shifted and crushed the drum allowing the liquid to escape.  The response crew collected all spill material using a suitable absorbent material and disposed of it along with the damaged drum at the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the vehicle was loaded, an inspection of the vehicle was conducted and no evidence of improper blocking and bracing was discovered.  Loading personnel have been re-instructed to insure that all containers are loaded in such a way that under conditions normally incident to transportation, individual containers are loaded in such a way that the void space between containers is minimized to prevent containers from shifting and damaging other freight.

column168: This shipment was offered to Hapag-Lloyd from Houston, Texas on the Veracruz Express Voyage 61E26 as non-hazardous cargo.    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed from Houston of undeclared hazardous material loaded in the portable tanks.    The shipping papers accompanied the container did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials and the tanks were not placarded and/or marked.    The shipper subsequentially provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column168: At approximately 7:00am on August 3, 2007 a van trailer stored at Clean Harbors Environmental Services 10-day in-transit storage yard located in Bridgeport, NJ experienced a minor release of hazardous waste material from a non-bulk package.  Upon opening a transport unit, an employee noticed a small amount of liquid material on a van trailer floor.  He immediately notified his supervisor of the spill and an in house emergency response crew was dispatched to identify the source of release and to take all necessary corrective actions.  Upon review of the paperwork, the emergency response crew donned appropriate protective equipment and entered the trailer.  An inspection of the non-bulk packages in the trailer identified that a single 5-gallon UN 1H1 container of Class 3 liquid material has developed a pin-hole near the top half of the container and began to seep out.  The response crew immediately used a chemically compatible absorbent material to contain approximately 1 gallons of liquid that was release to the floor of the trailer.   The leaking drum was placed in a suitable salvage drum and all of the absorbent was collected and placed into appropriate container for disposal at an approved hazardous waste management facility.  All of the released material was contained in the van trailer and no offsite impact occurred.
column169: Our investigation determined that the cause of the incident was deterioration of the container on storage and insufficient inspection prior to transportation.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported TILX 190013 with a product slosh emanating from the manway cover area during a normal switch movement and coupling in the railyard. TILX 190013 was cordoned off awaiting detailed inspection. BNSF contract responders inspected TILX 190013 and reported finding the manway securement bolts tight and sufficient product outage; but the manway gasket was missing between the manway nozzle and the manway cover. A new Buna 20 inch gasket was installed and the manway cover was properly secured. All spillage had evaporated and no ground impact was evident. Also, the bottom outlet cap (BOC) was found to be less than tool tight and the bottom outlet valve's (BOV) operating handle was not pinned. The BOC was tool tightened and the BOV handle was pinned. Response was concluded by 2330 hrs. MDT, 8/13/07. No additional product spillage was reported during subsequent rail movements of TILX 190013.

CN mechanical department employee noted product coming fromthe top of tank car during Yard inspection at the CN Pokegema Yard, Superior, WI. All appropriate departments notified and tank car isolated. CN Dangerous Goods Team responded noting leaking liquid line valve. Valve bolts tightened and leak stopped. Car released for movement to destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: APRX 6013, Argon, Refrigerated Liquid, was noted leaking liquid from inside its fittings' cabinet while at the CSX Transportation, Clark Avenue Yard, Cleveland, OH on 08/16/07 at 1538 hours, by a CSX Transportation Car Inspector. Messrs. T. Caldwell, DTO, R. Hinds, Trainmaster and J. Nagy, Yardmaster, all CSX Transportation, contacted T. J. Mannas, Manager-Hazardous Material Field Systems, CSX Trqansportation at 1607 hours, 08/16/2007. Mr. Nagy advised  representatives of the consignee were on site inspecting APRX 6013. Mr. Nagy advised the release was indeed a liquid release and not "venting". Consignee's representative on hand advised T. J. Mannas that the release was due to the liquid "fill" line valve being open less than 1/8 turn, due to the "securement strap" for the operating wheel of this valve not being in place and this valve vibrating loose during transit. Consignee representative had tightened the valve and leak stopped. "Securement strap" was properly placed against the operating wheel of the "fill" valve. Car was released for transportation. Consignee is a very short distance from the yard.     Cause Code:  307  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On August 1st at 0906 hours, CSX Train Q61830 was departing Maxwell Yard in Greenwood, South Carolina when a yard conductor reported smelling an unusual odor from one of the tank cars in the consist.  The train dispatcher and crew were notified and the outbound train was brought to a stop on the main line track at Mile Post SG425.8 (Oak Street) in Greenwood.  CSX Transportation immediately implemented their emergency response plan.  CSX management and the local fire department were contacted to respond to the scene.  Chemtrec was notified (Report Number 2007080100070) and the shipper; Transammonia was informed of the suspected release.  In addition, Hepaco Environmental was contacted by CSX to respond and secure the container.  Once on site, the first responders were able to detect a very slight intermittent odor from the ground next to Tank Car GAMX9296.  As a precautionary measure, the Greenwood Fire Department notified the nearest residence (Maxwell Children's Home) of the incident and issued a voluntary evacuation.  The residents followed the advice of the fire department and relocated to another building on the property.  After obtaining the appropriate personal protective equipment, the first responders along with Hepaco representatives opened the protective housing cover of the container and found the release was being emitted from the liquid eduction line gate valve.  Although the valve was properly closed and the plug was tool tight, intermitted vapors bypassed through the threads of the plug.  Hepaco removed and reapplied teflon tape to the plug.  The secondary closure plug was replaced and tightened with a wrench securing the container.  After ensuring all agencies involved (Greenwood Fire Department and South Carolina DHEC) were satisfied that the rail car would no longer release any vapors, it was decided to forward the train to Monroe Yard in Monroe, North Carolina, where the car would be set off awaiting an FRA Movement Exemption.  Upon arrival, the tank car was once again reinspected to ensure proper securement.  Hepaco was requested to continue daily inspection of the railcar until the shipper obtained an FRA Movement Exemption.  On August 2nd, Transammonia obtained FRA Movement Exemption Number FRA-07080235.  After properly stenciling the tank car and adding the exemption information into the waybill, the car was released to destination.  The car arrived at final destination (Honeywell - Hopewell, VA) without further incident on August 9th.  It is estimated that the car lost approximately one quart of product via vapors into the atmosphere.   Cause Code:  300  NARRI:  5(5+9+0) X (2+4) = 420

column168: On August 3rd at 1900 hours, a CSX Mechanical Department employee working in Florence Yard observed product dripping from the bottom outlet of tank car DOWX6235 (Load - Sodium Hydroxide).  CSX management immediately implemented their emergency response plan and isolated the area around the tank car.  Chemtrec was notified (Report Number 2007080300209) and the car owner; Dow Chemical was informed of the release.  CSX contracted Hepaco Environmental to respond and secure the container.  Once on site, Hepaco representatives found the top operated bottom outlet valve open approximately 1/4 turn.  The valve was then properly closed and the bottom outlet was re-checked for signs of leakage.  Unfortunately, closing the top operated bottom outlet valve did not contain the leak.  Hepaco loosened the bottom outlet auxiliary valve and plug, re-applied teflon tape to the threads, then tightened both with a wrench and the leak subsided.  Dow Chemical was informed that the car may have a defective bottom outlet valve and that they must apply for a FRA Movement Exemption.  The car was placed in bad order status and moved to the car shop repair track.  Approximately two gallons of product was released from the container.    Cause Code:  551  NARRI:  5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) =  100

column168: On 8/15/07 at 16:30 hrs., the trainmaster at CSX Transportation Stanley Yard, reported that tank car, GATX 46166, residue Methanol, was leaking from the bottom outlet. The car was isolated and a container was placed under bottom outlet nozzle to contain leak.  CSXT emergency response contractor, Eagle Construction + Environmental Services, Inc., (ECESI) was contacted to respond to the scene.  Upon arrival, ECESI tightened the top operating rod for the bottom outlet internal plug valve, two full turns to close the bottom outlet valve. ECESI  found the packing for the "stuffing box" of the top operated bottom outlet rod insufficient to secure the rod and added packing to the "stuffing box" and secured the operating rod in place. The car was checked with a CGA and no further leaks were noted. Car was secured and released for destination.    Cause Code:  568  NARRI:  5 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  Upon opening the trailer doors, a leak was detected in the shipment.  The trailer doors were closed and the trailer was isolated.  United States Environmental Services, LLC of La Porte, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  United States Environmental Services, LLC investigated the trailer and discovered one leaking 55-gallon drum.  Approximately one gallon of free product was released.  The damage to the drum was due to a puncture by a nail.  United States Environmental Services, Inc. applied absorbent pads to contain the free liquid on the impacted surface.  The damaged drum and the cleanup materials were placed into an over-pack drum.  One over-pack drum containing the damaged drum and cleanup materials was generated as a result of the incident.  United States Environmental Services, LLC will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident. No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and may have been related to a puncture by a nail, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence. However, Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: A BNSF train crew reported entrained GATX 300436 (DOT IIIA6OWI) dripping product from the bottom outlet valve (BOy). All train traffic was held until a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 300436. Responder reported that the top operated bottom outlet valve’s (TOBOV) operating rod was two turns open, the rod’s packing gland nut (PGN) was 1 1/2 turns loose and the BOV’s bottom outlet cap (BOC) was 1/4 turn less than tool tight. The responder closed the TOBOV, tightened the PGN and the BOC. Securement was completed and the product release ended prior to 1327 hrs. CDT, 8/06/07. All spillage appeared to evaporate. A BNSF contract environmental responder inspected the spill site, finding minimal ground impact from this product release; and applied ‘micro-blaze’ upon the ground at the spill site.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Driver's tractor broke down while pulling a loaded cargo tank.  While the driver was waiting for a vendor to be towed, the police stopped to direct traffic around the truck. A bucket was put under it and the local hazmat response team was called out.  The drip stopped when they were able to coast the unit to a flat surface.  It was just a couple of miles to the consignee so it was decided to get another tractor hooked to the load, take it to the consignee and get the trailer offloaded as soon as possible.  This was okayed by a gentleman that was a member of the local hazmat team that responded and also worked at the consignee.  This was done successfully.
column169: The trailer was washed and inspected to determine what caused the product to drip from the cargo tank. column168: On August 9, 2007, at approximately 0806 hours, a railway container EMPU 289353, loaded with 432 buckets of Corrosive liquid, basic, inorganic, N.O.S., UN3266 PG III, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Dallas, Texas yard. The container contained buckets of floor stripper and floor finisher which was damaged from not being properly blocked and braced.. The shipper representative responded to the site unloaded the entire shipment and inspected and wiped down the containers, and properly disposed all the empty containers. There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.      CODE: 662 (other)  Inner packaging, leaked, inadequate blocking and bracing    NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (3+0) =120    Identification Markings: 1H2Y43S07
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line as non-hazardous material by Atlantic Container Line (ACL), on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel St. Louis Express from Charleston, South Carolina to Southampton.    ACL advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed from Charleston that the shipment was not booked as hazardous materials, the shipping papers did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials, and that the container was no placarded and/or marked.  ACL subsequently provided ocrrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: After rail interchange from the BNSF to APA (Apache Railway Co.), the APA rejected UTLX 640566 due to dried product residue on its side shell. This stain appeared to have emanated from the manway area. BNSF contract responders inspected UTLX 640566 and reported finding two of eight manway securement bolts at the 3 and 5 o'clock positions only finger tight; and the manway gasket was partially hanging outside of the manway lip. The combination of the loose manway cover securement and the misaligned manway gasket prevented a good seal and contributed to the product release during rail movement. The product outage was deemed sufficient. Responders correctly repositioned the manway gasket and properly secured the manway lid. The product spillage on the tank shell was neutralized and cleaned off. No ground impact was evident. Response was concluded by 1215 hrs. MDT, 8/17/07.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: UTLX 642957 was noted by carrier personnel with product on the side of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, React Environmental, responded and found material leaking from around the base of the threaded liquid line valve.      The valve was removed, teflon tape applied and the valve reinstalled and properly tightened stopping the release.      Note this was a residue shipment leaking from the top of the car.  Apparently enough liquid material remained in the bottom of the car for heat related pressure build-up to force the liquid up the liquid line causing the material to be released from the threaded valve threads.

column62: Corrosion - Exterior; Defective Component or Device
column168: A BNSF mechanical carman whom was inspecting railcars in the railyard, reported GATX 61316 leaking product from the top fitting area. BNSF and contract responders inspected GATX 61316 and found the blind flange atop the liquid eduction line was the product leak source. This four bolt blind flange had two C-type washers that encompassed two bolt heads and nuts each. One C-type washer was corroded and allowed one bolt head to be pulled through this washer. This allowed the bolt's compression and the flange securement to loosen. The compromised flange sealing combined with internal tank car pressure build-up due to high ambient temperatures, allowed product to be forced out from under the blind flange. Responders changed out two bolts and applied new individual washers to the bolted connections over the C-type washers, resecuring the blind flange by 0330 hrs. CDT, 8/17/07. BNSF cable seal numbered 001251 was applied atop the secured blind flange. A BNSF environmental contractor neutralized all spillage on the tank shell and onto a very small amount of ground impact spillage. The tank shell of GATX 61316 was water washed clean by noon CDT, 8/17/07.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

WHEN THE DRIVER SHUT THE VALVE ON THE CUSTOMERS UNLOADING LINE, HE ATTEMPTED TO LET AIR IN THE LINE USING THE QUICK COUPLING ON THE END OF HIS HOSE.THE HOSE CAME OFF THE UNLOADING LINE SPRAYING PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AND ON THE DRIVER.

column168: During an inbound BNSF train inspection, intermodal container JBHU 222697 was found to be leaking an unknown clear resin type substance from under the rear container doors and onto the entrained rail flatcar platform. The flatcar was setout of the train and JBHU 222697 was removed from the flatcar. Inspection of JBHU 222697 revealed eight 5-gallon steel pails loosely wrapped on a pallet with flammable labeling at the rear of the load near the doorway. This shipment was not itemized on the hazardous material billing received and on file. One bottom pail on the pallet had a cut on its sidewall towards the bottom of the pail which appeared to be from a forklift tine. This cut allowed all product within to ooze out. The compromised pail was overpacked and returned to the load after JBHU 222697 was cleaned. JBHU 222697 was reloaded onto the same rail flatcar after its platform was cleaned of all spillage. After arriving at its rail destination (in Portland, OR), JBHU 222697 was noted that not all the former spillage at the rear of the container and chassis was removed. The interior lading was inspected and found to be secure. Shipper contractor cleaned the remaining dried spillage and JBHU 222697 was released to be outgated from the BNSF intermodal facility at Portland.    The material in the pail was labeled as being manufactured by Superior Stone Products, Inc. and identified as Superior Transparent Flowing, a polyester adhesive and filler. The product MSDS indicated that this is a DOT regulated hazardous material classified as Resin Solution, Class 3, UN 1866, PG III.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: At approximately 7:45am on August, 17 2007 a release of hazardous waste onto a van trailer floor and a secondary containment pad occurred from a non-bulk container.  At the time of the release, an employee was loading non-bulk containers of hazardous waste into a tractor trailer at a 10-day transfer facility operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services (CHES) in Reidsville, NC.   While loading a pallet of cargo onto the trailer utilizing a forklift, an employee punctured a 55 gallon metal drum containing Flammable Liquid, UN1993 that was already in the trailer with the fork-lift fork that was protruding past the pallet being loaded.  The fork punctured the metal drum releasing all of its contents within seconds.      Upon realizing that a release had occurred, the employee immediately evacuated the area and notified his supervisor.  The area was blocked off and all sources of ignition were eliminated.  An in-house spill response crew was dispatched an arrived to the location shortly  They retrieved and reviewed the shipping papers and determined that the material in the drum was Waste Flammable Liquids, n.o.s 3 UN1993, PGIII    After reviewing the shipping papers, the response crew utilizing appropriate personal protection equipment and company health and safety policies and procedures entered the trailer and commenced the clean up operations.  At the time of the release, the trailer was parked in a concrete containment pad and any material that was released from the trailer was confined to the pad.  All of the released material was absorbed using a compatible absorbent and placed in to appropriate containers for future disposal at a permitted hazardous waste disposal facility.      The clean up operation was completed without any further incidents and no of-site impact occurred.
column169: Human error contributed mostly to this release of hazardous materials.  The driver of the forklift as well as all other employees at this location were reminded of proper cargo handling and fork lift operation.  A need for fork-lift re-evaluation is also being considered in response to this spill.

column168: The packages came into the Frankfurt Customs clearence area. The Customs inspector chose to hand-inspect the shipment. Upon opening the box, one of the batteries arced, caught fire & began emitting strong fumes. The fire was extinguished by local personnel. There were no Dangerous Goods markings, labeling or shipping papers that would have led us to believe the contents were regulated. The FAA has been notified, I spoke to SA Janet McLaughlin.

The shipment was refused by the recipient. During the refusal process, the recipient remarked to our Courier that the package contained perfume. The package was returned to the FedEx station where it was opened. We found 13-3.3 ounce bottles of perfume. There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The FAA was notified, I left a message for SA. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection.

During cargo operations this shipment was noticed to have an strong odor and slight leak. Closer inspection revealed a box of nail polish. The MSDS from the shipper indicates this material is a Class 3 flammable liquid. The shipment was not marked, labeled, or documented to contain dangerous goods. The shipment is being held pending FAA investigation. The local FAA office was notified.

Our Driver was rear ended.  When this happened one 20 pound cylinder was punctured. The size of the hole was smaller than a dime. The punctured cylinder was taken away from the accident scene. Our truck was mostly filled with empty cylinders.
column169: The driver did everything he could to keep the accident scene safe.  Since this accident was beyond our control I can not make any further recommendations.

column168: THE SHIPPER TENDERED 11pc WEIGHING 1240k AT SEA AA AIR CARGO FOR TRANSPORT TO JFK THEN CONNECTING WITH AUSTRIAN AIRLINES TO THE FINAL DESTINATION IN LITHUANIA. ON THE AIRWAY BILL, IT WAS STATED THAT CARGOLOGIC, USA WAS A KNOWN SHIPPER TO AUSTRIAN AIRLINES. AFTER ACCEPTING THE SHIPMENT, THE CARGO AGENT NOTICED A MSDS MIXED IN THE PAPERWORK. THIS TRIGGERED THE THOUGHT THAT THERE MAY BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS IN THE SHIPMENT. UPON FURTHER REVIEW OF THE MSDS IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS AN OXIDIZING SOLID, N.O.S. THE SHIPMENT WAS OPENED AND INDEED, ONE OF THE BOXES CONTAINED 12 JARS OF JOE-GLO AT 12 OZ. EACH. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF ANY SUBSTANCE INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. AT THIS POINT IN TIME, THE LOCAL FAA OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN SEA. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, AN EMPLOYEE FROM THE FAA CAME TO INSPECT THE SHIPMENT. HE ADVISED AA TO REFUSE THE SHIPMENT AND RETURN IT TO THE SHIPPER. THE SHIPPER CAME AND PICKED UP THE SHIPMENT. LATER THAT DAY, THE SAME SHIPMENT WAS RE-TENDERED TO AA WITH A MODIFIED MSDS. THE CARGO AGENT REFUSED THE SHIPMENT AND ALERTED ME OF THE INCIDENT. I CONTACTED AN EMPLOYEE FROM FAA AND ADVISED HIM OF THE SITUATION.
column169: HAVE ADVISED SHIPPER THAT SHIPMENT WAS NOT LABELED WITH A DANGEROUS GOODS AND THE DANGEROUS GOOD WAS NOT DECLARED.

column168: Driver pulled into parking lot and noticed substance leaking out the back of his trailer.  Immediately investigated and discovered a drum was leaking from a puncture to the side of it.  Turned drum on its side and secured drum to prevent anymore leaking.  Used spill diapers to clean up the small amount that had fallen into the parking lot.  Local Ashland facility sent two people to the scene with overpack drum and more clean up items.  Once spill had been cleaned up on the ground and in the trailer all spill clean up realated items and leaking drum were put into an overpack drum.  Trailer along with overpak drum were moved to local Ashland facility less than 5 minutes away.
column169: Training was conducted at the loading facility to make sure warehouse employees were loading drums onto our trucks properly to prevent damage to the packaging.  Also drivers were instructed to make sure that they look over their loads at each stop to make sure no damage was done to the products still on their truck during the unloading process.  Will continue to stock trucks and trailers with such equipment as spill diapers, overpak drums, and drum sealer.

column168: Driver was proceeding westbound on I-80 approximately 25 miles southwest of Winnemucca, NV, when he noticed a mist trailing his vehicle in the rearview mirror. Driver pulled off freeway at Exit 158 (Cosgrove Rest Area), turned left under the freeway overpass, and proceeded to the rest area where he parked the vehicle.    Of the estimated <100 gallons of ferric chloride solution that spilled to the roadway, the majority of it was located under the overpass. A thin trail of material was also spilled on the access road to the rest area. No material was released to the land or waterways. The active leak ceased when the driver parked the vehicle.    The driver notified a Nevada Highway Patrol officer that was in the vicinity, and the NHP closed the rest stop and access road. Vehicles that were parked in the rest area were not allowed to leave because they would have to have driven through the spilled material (the rest stop has only one road as a means of ingress/egress). Drivers of the quarantined vehicles were transported to Winnemucca and were provided with hotel rooms for the duration of the cleanup.    An emergency response contractor was brought in to neutralize the spilled material with sodium bicarbonate solution and water. The roadway was pressure washed and decontamination liquids were collected with a vactor truck. The remaining liquid on the tanker was offloaded into poly totes, and all materials were transported to PSC's hazardous waste facility in Fernley, NV.     Upon inspection, a small corrosion hole was found in the bottom 90-degree elbow of the tanker's standpipe. It is assumed that liquid movement in the tank had allowed material to enter the standpipe, and the material was released through the hole. The tanker has been taken out of service, and is currently being repaired in Tacoma, WA.    Notification of the incident was provided immediately to the Nevada Department of Environmental Protection, EPA Region 9, and to the NRC (report #844762).
column169: The tanker was taken out of service and is currently being repaired. Periodic thickness testing will be undertaken to ensure the tanker's integrity is maintained.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon offloading at consignee location, Heartland Paper Company, A&R Transport, Inc. discovered a leak coming from the trailer.  Area was isolated and a Material Safety Data Sheet was referenced.  Ecolab, Inc., the shipper of the product, was contacted to assess the situation.  Coteau Environmental of Watertown, South Dakota was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Coteau Environmental detected free product on the asphalt parking lot, and inside the trailer.  Coteau Environmental utilized absorbent pads and applied a neutralizing agent to the free product.  Site was secured, pending the arrival of proper equipment to offload the trailer.  Upon offloading the trailer, eleven (11) 5-gallon drums of formic acid, and seven (7)   5-gallon drums of sodium hydroxide were discovered damaged.  The damaged drums were overpacked into two (2) separate recovery drums.  Coteau Environmental proceeded to use floor dry and absorbent material on the trailer floor.  The spent floor dry, absorbent material, and neutralized product were placed into two (2) recovery drums.  Four(4) recovery drums were generated during cleanup efforts.  Trailer was reloaded with remainder of freight, and sent on.  Disposal will be coordinated directly by Coteau Environmental in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to the freight being damaged in transit, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: A BNSF train derailed its rear six railcars on main track due to one derailed railcar with a brake valve malfunction (stuck brake). Two tank cars ladened with hazardous materials derailed with ACFX 95599 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) derailing on its side. ACFX 95599 leaked product from the fill hole cover. The local F.D. placed a pool receptacle under the leak to capture the spillage. A BNSF contract responder tightened the three fill hole securement bolts which ended any further product release by 1300 hrs. CDT, 8/17/07. The pool receptacle captured approximately six gallons of the leaking product. All spillage was neutralized. ACFX 95599 was uprighted; the remaining product in ACFX 95599 was transferred into tanker trucks and delivered to the consignee. ACFX 95599 was cleaned and purged by 8/31/07.

column168: 8/23/07: Approximately 2:45AM; CR crew FP-50 switching customer Basic Chemical Solutions, Fairless, Morrisville, PA, coupled to tank car TCIX 21090, residue Hydrochloric Acid, located on the customer lead.  Crew then went inside the plant, pulled 6 cars from customer unloading spots as instructed and pulled out to the Fairless yard to drop off 6 cars and replace TCIX 21090 into the lead/plant as it had not been ordered out.    While conductor was standing at switch and cars began to move, he noted TCIX 21090 with vapor from top of car, which initiated coughing and vomiting from him.  He was later examined and released with no further problems by local EMT and hospital as a precautionary measure.    Further investigation by CR Risk Mgmt. A. Richter; emergency response contractor REACT G. Bunker; and customer's R. Daigle (Basic Chemical), noted liquid eduction pipe was severely corroded at the pipe's mounting flange connection.  Additionally, 3 threaded securement bolts were corroded and/or loose at the base.  This car was not being offered for transportation but had to be moved to get to other cars ordered out by the customer.    Car was moved back inside the customer's facility, for their further handling.

column168: Tank Vehicle was turning left onto northbound I-15 from eastbound Friars road. The driver turned too sharply and/or too fast, which lead to a loss of control, and the vehicle fell on it's right side. The tank fell onto a signpost that created a 3 inch punture to the right side of the cargo tank wall. Response crew recovered approx 2500 gallons of gasoline into recovery pump truck. The cargo tank leaked gasoline contents for approx 4 hours before the tank contents were fully removed. Sand dikes were contructed to contain the released gasoline. After the tank was set upright with crane trucks, pooled product was immediately recovered, and within 10 days, contaminated soils were removed from the shoulder area and disposed. Approx 100 gallons reached the storm drains, which were completely cleaned the next day. All recovery and remediation efforts were supervised by appropriate regulatory agency personel.
column169: The accident investigation shown that there were no contributing factors to the accident, other that poor driver judgment. Cargo was loaded properly, there were no mechanical defects on the 6 month old vehicle, and the driver was not impaired or distracted. It is estimated that the driver had completed the turn several hundred times in the past without incident. The driver has been terminated, and efforts to increase driver awareness, and elininate driver complacency, have been implemented. These measures include: increased training, visual reminders, verbal reminders, and "Safe Driving Incentives".

column168: A BNSF railcar inspector reported an ammonia odor in the railyard near the vicinity of GATX 201606 and GATX 201590 that were standing on an adjacent yard track from the inspector. Both of these tank cars were cordoned off and yard operations were ceased. The local F.D. responded and inspected both tank cars, finding only a very slight odor near these railcars and departed after this determination. BNSF and shipper responders inspected these two tank cars and reported finding a slight vapor release from the pressure relief device (PRD) atop GATX 201606 (a DOT 112J340W tank car). Shipper responder replaced both o-rings in the PRD of GATX 201606 which ended the vapor release/product odor by 2240 hrs. PDT, 8/19/07. Responders also reported that the inspection of GATX 201590 revealed that it was not leaking product; and all valves and fittings were secure. Rail operations in the railyard were resumed after GATX 201606 was secured.   On 8/22/07 (at approximately 1700 hrs. PDT), an ammonia odor was again reported in the Riverbank railyard. Rail operations were ceased and five loaded tank cars of anhydrous ammonia in the railyard were identified as possible odor sources. BNSF and shipper responders inspected these tank cars finding four of them secure and the fifth, GATX 201606, again as the odor source. Shipper responder replaced the o-rings in the PRD atop GATX 201606 by 2115 hrs. PDT, 8/22/07, which eliminated the vapor release/product odor emanating from GATX 201606. Railyard operations were resumed afterwards.   Evidently, during the 8/19/07 PRD o-ring change performed on GATX 201606, the o-rings slipped slightly out of position and were partially pinched or flattened, which prevented a good seal and necessitated replacement.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

CONWAY CALLED THE CONTACT PERSON AT NALCO, MARY, AND SHE RECOMMENDED TO CALL CHEMTEC. CONWAY REPORTED INCIDENT TO CHEMTEC TO WYMAN, RESPONDER #9 TOOK REPORT. CONWAY CALLED NRC ENVIRONMENTAL TO DO CLEANUP AT LYDEN'S LOCATION. NRC REP FOUND LEAKAGE TO BE OLD, HARD AND STICKLY. AFTER CLEANING UP FREIGHT, LEAKAGE SHOWED COMING OUT OF A LOOSE BOLT ON COVER OF TOTE. HE MOVED TOTE AROUND WITH FORKLIFT TO SEE IF THERE WAS ANYMORE LEAKAGE (SLOSH TEST). SMALL AMOUNT WAS FOUND AND HE TIGHTENED ALL BOLTS AND REDID SLOSH TEST. NO MORE LEAKAGE WAS FOUND AND HE REPORTED THAT IT WAS SAFE FOR FREIGHT TO BE SHIP ON TO ALASKA.

column168: ON 08/20/07 AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, AFTER FILLING THE VEHICLE MOUNTED VESSEL (VMV), OUR SERVICE TECHNICIAN FAILED TO DISCONNECT THE FILL HOSE FROM BULK STARAGE TANK. HE REALIZED HIS ERROR AS HE BEGAN TO DRIVE AWAY. AND IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE VEHICLE-BUT NOT BEFORE STRETCHING THE FILL-HOSE TO THE EXTENT IT CAUSED THE 90 DEGREE ELOW OF THE FILL HOSE CONNECTOR ON THE VMV TO SPLIT. DAMAGE SUSTAINED FROM THE INCIDENT RESULTED IN A RELATIVELY SLOW LEAKAGE OF PRODUCT FROM THE VMV. MAXIMUM VOLUME OF LEAKED PRODUCT WAS 119 GALLONS, WHICH WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE CARGO AREA OF THE DELIVERY VEHICLE. BULK STORAGE TANK PLUMBING RECEIVED NEGLIGIBLE COSMETIC DAMAGE THAT DID NOT COMPROMISE ITS INTEGRITY.
column169: ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE WERE AS FOLLOW: EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR INCIDENT RECEIVED WRITTEN REPRIMAND FOR NON-COMPLIANCE TO BRANCH SPECIFIC POLICIES REGARDING FILL PROCESS FROM BULK STORAGE TANK TO VEHICLE MOUNTED VESSEL. THIS DICIPLINARY ACTION WAS PLACED IN THE EMPLOYEES PERSONNEL FILE. SAME EMPLOYEE WAS RE-EDUCATED ON BRANCH-SPECIFIC POLICES ON FILL PROCESS FROM BULK STORAGE TANK TO VEHICLE-MOUNTED VESSEL. EMPLOYEE WAS OBSERVED PERFOMING A VESSEL FILL USING PROPER TECHIQUE BEFORE BEING ALLOW TO RESUME THE FILL PROCESS UNSUPERVISED. EMPLOYEE WILL BE RE-OBSERVED PERFOMRING FILLS ON A RANDOM, UNANNOUNCED BASIS GOING FOWARD FOR THE NEXT 2 MONTHS.

column168: No additional comments.   UTLX 203199 was reported to be continuously leaking from the top protective housing while sitting in the yard, product flowing down the sides of the rail car. The local yardmaster called the shipper and responded Gary Turner at 1600 hrs.Their inspection found the liquid line valve leaking at the base where it is threated to the nipple. The valve was removed, teflon tape was applied to the threads and the valve was secured. On 08/03/07 the car was noted to be leaking again from the top protective housing. Re-inspection by the shipper determined the valve threads were gouged and damaged at the liquid induction threaded nipple. The product pressure increased under the direct heat and high humidity and created a slow but consistent release of the product from the damaged threads. The valve was removed by the shipper and replaced with a new pipe cap. The car was observed later and no further leaks or releases were noted. The shipper applied to the FRA for movement approval forwarding this car.

THE TANK BEING FILLED WAS LOCATED IN A SPILLED CONTAINMENT AREA WHCIH ELIMINATED ANY FLOW POTENTIAL. WE HAVE SINCE, REPLACED THE NOZZLE THAT FAILED AND HAVE NOT HAD ANY REOCCURRENCES.

column168: The customer notified the port of a hazardous vehicle shipment after the cargo had been received, loaded to the cargo vessel and shipped.  Updates were made to the shipment record to reflect the actual shipment as the class 9 vehicle.  This type of situation occurs regularly due to the difference in the vehicle shipping status over water versus over land.  Customers familiar with the land procedures do not take the time to become familiar with 49CFR173.220 and 49CFR176.905.
column169: The shipper documentation should provide information pertaining to whether a shipment is hazardous or non hazardous on his bill of lading.  If they declare the shipment as non hazardous, they should cite the referebce which allows them to opt out of the requlations.  Routine inspections periodically show vehicle shipments as hazardous when initially declared as non hazardous.

column168: Tank was found with damaged and/or leaking valves (cause undetermined) upon arrival (via highway) at the port terminal. Once the spill was reported, the tank was relocated to a safety zone until the leak could be remediated. A representative of the shipper (from Matheson Trigas) arrived at the scene and determined the cause of the leak to be a loose stem valve. The valve was re-tightened and monitored for 30 minutes to verify no further leakage. Subsequently, the shipment was deemed transportation-worthy and, therefore, rendered in compliance with the applicable regulations. END OF REPORT

column168: 6:15AM Driver Allen Enocencio reported incident along with approximate size and that source was immediately controlled to Operations Manager Michael Kaneda who was already on his way to work.  6:20AM Michael called Clean Islands Council (CIC) to report spill and solicited assistance.  6:25AM Michael called V.P. Mark Leong to report incident as well as calling the Hawaii Petroleum’s warehouse supervisor Kimo Grace as well as his warehouse worker Lionel Haili to assist in clean up, Michael also called Shirleen Nases the dispatcher to notity the Coast Guard.  6:35AM Michael arrived at spill event at Hilo Pier 3 and assisted Allen in containing, absorbing as well as cleaning pier. During our cleaning of the pier Allen and Michael reviewed incident, while Allen was checking connections of suction hose that runs from trailer to truck he saw that product was starting to spray from hose connection at truck which fell of just as he was about to grab it. Allen then immediately shut off the product at the trailer. He then started trying to contain what he could, after that he radioed Michael.  6:40AM Sheldon Lehman and Mike Thomas from CIC arrived, we reviewed situation and Sheldon immediately started deploying sorbant sweep from pier 3 all the way around pier 2 1/2 to the end of pier 2 to for containment while Mike brought around CIC’s boat. We then tied sorbant sweep to the back of the boat to form a V then pulled the sweep around the harbor to pick up ary product that had escaped before the containment was set up around the pier.  6:42AM Michael called National Response Center to report incident and spoke to Rawls who after having received required information assigned Report # 847236.  6:45AM Kimo arrived with more sorbant pads and assisted in cleaning pier.  6:45AM Michael called Shirleen to verify Coast Guard was called.  6:47AM Michael called State Department of Health Heer to report Spill.  7:00AM Michael received call from HEER Elizabeth Galvez to gover incident and she assigned case # 20070829-0659.  7:10AM Lionel Haili arrived and started assisting Kimo in the pier clean up.  8:55AM Called John Ross the LEPC Civil Defense.  9:00AM Primary containment completed around piers but cruise ship was coming in and Sheldon was concerned with the extra movement of water that would occur when the bow thrusters were used to dock so he suggested we deploy a secondary containment just in case any product got by the first containment as well s running sorbet sweep along the shore line as a precautionary measure.  9:05AM Petty Officer Fallon of the Coast Guard called for an assessment so I brought him up to date on incident.  9:15AM Kimo and Lionel completed cleaning what was on pier 3 and went back to warehouse.  9:30AM Liz Galvaz from HEER requested pictures so I picked up our digital camera and took pictures of CIC boat pulling sorbant sweep outside piers searching for any possible signs of product as well as the sorbant deployed around pier.  10:00AM Seconda

column168: No injuries to report    No road arteries affected    Upon tank container number SCZU 873892-3 arrival into the outbound EIR lane of Penn Terminals, it was discovered by the Penn Terminals checker that ethyl alcohol was dripping out of the vent tube. The checker sent the driver, Quality Carrier, into our office to report it. I immediately went out to assess the situation. The tank container showed no visible sign of damage. The drip was moving at a rate of one drop every five seconds. I had the driver notify his dispatcher and I notified the owner of the tank, Diageo Relay. I notified the Terminal Manager of the situation and he had the tank container segregated in a safe area, away from cargo and human traffic.  The owner sent in Broomall Truck repair service under the advice of Quality Carrier.  Harry Broomall arrived at 1600hrs and checked all the seals on the tank container. After a few adjustments, he stopped the drip.  I checked the tank container again after an hour and there were no signs of dripping.  I notified the owner that the problem was solved. Quality Carrier retrieved the tank container on 9/5 @ 0927hrs.    Commodity Ethyl Alcohol   Class 3  UN # 1170  Packing Group II  Flashpoint 17 degrees C  22540 liters     END OF REPORT

column168: A BNSF switch crew member reported an acid type odor and alleged vapor inhalation while in the BNSF railyard. Two additional switch crew members also complained of inhalation exposure. All three employees were taken to a local hospital for examination and released with diagnosis unknown at this time. The BNSF Assistant Director Hazardous Materials responded and reported finding GATX 60976 (DOT 111A1OOW5) at theincident site with a ruptured 165 psi frangible disc in the safety vent. Air monitoring was initiated by the responder. No detectable readings of hydrochloric acid were found at ground level or at the top of GATX 60976, although some level was detected at the frangible disc orifice in the safety vent. The responder plugged the safety vent orifice, as no replacement 4 3/4 inch frangible disc was readily available. A very small amount of drying residue product around the safety vent was wiped. GATX 60976 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard at the repair track awaiting replacement disc application. At 1000 hrs. CDT on 8/07/07, a BNSF contractor installed the appropriate replacement frangible disc on GATX 60976 without further incident.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported GATX 49476 (DOT 111A100W1) expelling a small amount of product from the top of this tank car during normal switching operations in the railyard. The rail movement was stopped. GATX 49476 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. Initial inspection by a local BNSF responder indicated that the frangible disc in the safety vent atop GATX 49476 had ruptured. The shipper was contacted to replace the frangible disc but this could not be accomplished until mid-week. A BNSF contractor was then called to replace the frangible disc. BNSF contract responders replaced the ruptured 165 psi frangible disc in kind by 2142 hrs. CDT, 8/06/07. Responders also neutralized a small amount of dried residue product around the safety vent of GATX 49476. No ground impact was evident.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: In response to employee complaints of odor in the UPRR yard at Livonia, LA UPRR MTO John Valley and Tom Robinson, Manager Hazardous Materials Management conducted a search. This search resulted in the inspection of tank car RAIX 6398. The car was located on bowl track 30 and was leaking product from two locations on the top of the tank. The one leak was from beneath the liquid valve flange and the second leak was from the pressure relief valve. The tank was ina shell full condition. The leakage was estimated at about ten gallons per hour and was evaporating as it reached the ground.    The car was relocated onto the drip pans on track 105 at the Livonia yard without incident.    Robinson contacted United States Environmental Services (U.S.E.S), a response contractor and Mr. Joey Dugas of DOW Chemical, the responsible party. Arrangements were made and approximately 2000 gallons of product was removed from the overloaded tank car into a cargo tank truck. DOW will arrange for transportation of both the tank car and the cargo tank truck back to ODFJELL Terminals Houston, at Bayport, TX the point of origin.    After the tank car was relieved at the 2000 gallons of product, U.S.E.S personnel were able to tighten three of the four ecurement bolts on the liquid valve flange approximately three quarters of a turn each.    Supplemental: On Thursday, 8/9/07 Tank car RAIX 6398 was a gain inspected while on track 105 at the UPRR Livonia, LA rail yard by Mgr, Robinson. The car was found to be leaking a small amount of product from the liquid valve flange. Mr. Steve Dennis of Dow chemicals and technicians from U.S.E.S responded and the liquid valve and education tube flange gaskets were replaced without incident. The additional spillage was less than a cup and evaporated before it could flow down the side of the tank.

column168: 01:21 PM, Rick Sloane, Manager of Hazardous Materials, reported he was notified by Jason Wilkerson, Sr. Mgr. Transportation atE ugene, Or., of a release of hazardous materials from a tank car at Springfield, OR. Mr. Sloane advised a switch crew reported product was released from, and evaporated around the manway gasket on Tankcar AGCX 10076 while being moved within the Springfield Railyard. Mr. Sloane responded. He stated that the tankcar had been set out on Track 82 of the Springfield Railyard. There were no injuries, evacuations exposures, fires, or waterways affected. State regulatory notifications were issued. At 03:16 PM, Sloane advised he inspected the car and observed the manway gasket was out of alignment. column168: Dave Fisher, Manager of Terminal Operations, reported Tankcar TILX 262052 had released an unknown quantity of product from the top onto the sides of the tankcar in the the Hinkle Railyard in 1-lermiston, OR. RMCC notifed NDSiler, Mgr of Environmental Field Operations. Siler contacted National Response Corporation (NRC) of Portland, a contractor, to respond. Dave also stated three radyard employees were complained of nausea and dizziness after potentail exposure. Medical response team examined employees on sight and released them. Employees declined transport to hospital for further evaluation. NRC arrived on scene roughly 12:30 AM PDST on August 2nd. Determined release was caused by open liquid line valve. NRC removed hardened phenol, closed valve, re-sealed car and released to destination. Recovered, hardened Phenol and PPE placed in overpack drums which for disposal.

column168: John Hasse a part time dock worker was unloading a trailer this evening. He was removing skids that were infront of unprotected drums and accidnetly punctured adrum. column169: I will need to give Joh hasse additional training about unloading city breakers. However it would be nice for our shippers who ship loose drums to have dunnage to protect the drums or have the driver had the dunnage when he will be picking up multiple shipments of skids and loose drums.

column168: THE LIQUID VALVE IS A BALL TYPE VALVE. THE STEM WS IN THE CLOSED POSITION WHEN THE DRIVER REMOVED THE VALVE PLUG. I CALLED CHEMTREC AT APPROXIMATELY 15:00 TO REPORT A CARBON DIOXIDE RELEASE THE HUGHES SPRINGS TERMINAL MANAGER CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND CITY POLICE IN HUGHES SPRINGS, TX. TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE INCIDENT. AFTER AN HOUR OR SO THE VALVE VIBRATED ITSELF CLOSED TO THE POINT THE DRIVER COULD INSTALL THE FITTING ON THE RAILCAR AND CONTAIN THE RELEASE. THE RAILCAR WAS THEN UNLOADED INTO TRUCKS AND THE DEFECTIVE LIQUID VALVE WAS REPLACED BY A MOBILE RAIL CREW.

column168: KEITH FLEMING, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED HOPPERCAR AEX 1151 RELEASED PRODUCT AT THE WEST END OF WHEEL NINE, EAST YARD, SAN ANTONIO, TX. MR. FLEMING STATED THAT A LARGE PILE OF FERTILIZER WAS ON THE TRACK AND REPORTED NO INJURIES OR AFFECTED WATERWAYS. PAUL PERSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED, STATED HE WOULD PERFORM SITE REMEDIATION DURING DAYLIGHT HOURS. HEFURTHER ADVISED THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF A COUPLING BYPASS INCIDENT. STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE ISSUED. AT 06:09 AM, MR. PERSON ADVISED THAT THE RAILCAR COULD NOT BE MOVED DUE TO THE WHEELS BEING PUSHED UP AGAINST A BOTTOM BIN. MR. PERSON STATED APPROXIMATELY 1000 LBS WAS RELEASED AND WOULD BE SHOVELED INTO BAGS AND THE REMAINING AMOUNT WOULD BE TRANSLOADED.

WHILE BEING MOVED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS AT THE UPRR LIOVONIA, LA YARD, TANK CAR GATX 62562 EMITTED A SIGNIFICANT VAPOR CLOUD FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK. THE CAR WAS LOCATED TOWARD THE NORTH END OF BOWL TRACK 25. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED THERE WITH NO REPORTED EXPOSURES OR INJURIES. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE COMPLETED AND TOM ROBINSON, MGR HAZMAT MGMT RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE TANK CAR. THIS ISPECTION REVEALED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY HAD FAILED. ROBINSON REPLACED THAT DISC AND SECURED THECAR FROM LEAKING. AN ESTIMATED RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD RUN DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANK AND A SMALL AMOUNT HAD CONTACTED THE GROUND (RAILROAD BALLAST/ROCK). HULCHER PROFESSIONAL SERVICES WERE DISPATCHED AND USING A BAKING SODA SOLUTION, DECONTAMINATED THE SPILLAGE ON THE TANK CAR AND THE GROUND.

column168: Director of Terminal Operations, reported a release of product from railcar MDCX 1113 in the West Colton Railyard in Colton, CA. Employee stated the quantity released was unknown, it was coming from the top of the railcar, and he had cleared the area around the railcar for 100 yards. Manager of Hazardous Materials Management, was notified and stated he would take over the incident shortly, but, Manager of Hazardous Materials Management, would make the initial response, since he was in the area. At 09:40 PM, Bavier advised that the release had been stopped and that it had been caused by a rupture disc, which he replaced. The total amount of product on the top of the railcar was four gallons and approximately six ounces were on the ground. Employee stated the railcar would have to be decontaminated and the contractors would be handling the remediation, On 08/19/07, at 12:27 AM, another employee took over the incident and advised that employee, had replaced the rupture disk, and contractors had arrived on scene to decontaminate the rail car.

column168: CSX PSCC received a report at 0336 hours from South Kearny Terminal, Meadows Yard that a yard crew smelled the odor of chlorine. Local Trainmaster, Steve Makoski investigated with a CSXT Special Agent and smelled the odor and heard hissing coming from PROX 89215, Load UN1017 (Chlorine) on meadows yard track #6. The TERP (Transportation Emergency Response Plan) was initiated, and the area near the tank car was isolated. A CSXT Emergency Response Contractor was called to respond, and the consignee was notified. The local fire department and the county hazmat team also responded. The entry team comprised of the Hudson County HazMat Team, CSXT contractor, REACT Environmental Services and the consignee Kuehne Chemical Co. made entry and inspected the railcar. A vapor leak was detected between the PRD (Pressure Relief Device) at the base were the PRD is mounted, B-end right side. Unsuccessful attempts to tighten the stud nuts did not stop the leak. A chlorine âceC-Kitfl (capping kit) was applied to the PRD to mitigate the vapor leak. The car was expedited by CSXT personnel into the Kuehne Chemical Co. facility for emergency off-loading.  NARRI - 5(5+10+1)x(2+7)=720  Cause Code 408

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FOKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING OR TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL LIQUIZ AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: At approximately 06:45 AM on August 22, 2007 the facility I was removing ammonia vapor from, allowed liquid ammonia into the compressor system on the trailer without my knowledge. The liquid ammonia filled the compressor system on my trailer. Liquid is non compressible, therefore the pressure relief valve which is set at 250 psig released ammonia vapor for 50 to 55 seconds. Approximately 90 pounds of ammonia vapor was released in the surrounding area. All emergency shut devices were activated on the trailer and functioned properly. Water spray was used to knock down the ammonia vapor. There was no damage to the equipment.
column169: 1. Review the total system prior to pump out.  2. Insure lockout-tagout procedures are used.  3. Remove vapor from the high side of a system only.  4. Install additional safety shut down systems on compressor when liquid ammonia is present.  5. Additional training for Airgas ammonia employees.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS   WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING   BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK   MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FOKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING OR TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL LIQUIZ AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: Driver arrived at Allentown terminal. When he was putting his trailers in doors he noticed that the trailer had a smell coming from it and was dripping liquid from thefront of the trailer. Dockman unloaded trailer immediately. The shipment that was leaking was part of an 11 skid shipment. Conway records show that this shipment never moved from this trailer once it was picked up at shipper until it got to Conway facility in Allentown. When we got to the leaking skid, it was in the nose of the trailer. There were 11 pails damaged. 3 of them were leaking. Pails appear to have been damaged with forklift at shipper's facility when being put on our truck.

column168: Shipment arrived in Butte on a 28 foot semi trailer. While being unloaded with a fork lift at the dock a damp spot was noticed on the floor of the trailer. I (Larry McGillvray) was notified of the apparent leaking shipment. At that time that the spill was noticed the fork lift was shut off untill the leaking product could be identified.We identified the product and found that it was hazardous so the proper paper work was pulled and Chemtrec hotline was called for proper clean up and precautionary measures to be taken for clean up. We followed the clean up requiements and put the leaking containers in an over pack drum for proper disposition. The leaking containers had strarted leaking because of the pressure exerted on the bottom box from the weight of the boxes stacked on top of it. The weight forced the bottom containers to crush under the weight and split on the underside of the plastic bottles against the boards on the pallet.
column169: Use proper loading requirements so that the bottom boxes are not subject to over stress due to too much weight being placed on top of them causing them to be crushed under the load.

column169: TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND OR DUNNAGE. USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING LAYERS OF FREIGHT.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FOKLIFT. column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGE OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column169: FREIGHT HANDLER SHOULD EXERCISE CAUTION AND AWARENESS WHILE LOADING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES  OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BECOMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

TANKCAR GATX 57109 HAD A SMALL VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE PRESSURE PLATE. IN THE POCATELLO RAILYARD MILOVANOVIC ADVISED AIR SAMPLING SHOWS A ZERO DETECTABLE READING AROUND THE TANKCAR. MILOVANOVIC WAS UNABLE TO TIGHTEN THE BOLTS ON THE PRESSURE PLATE. THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS PACKED WITH ICE AND ABSORBED PADS TO STOP THE RELEASE, AND THE TANKCAR WAS SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER (SIMPLOT) FOR REPAITS.    TANKCAR GATX 57109 HAD PREVIOUSLY LEAKED IN THE POCATELLO RAILYARD ON 07/29/2007 AND SENT TO SIMPLOT'S DON PLANT FOR REPAIR, SIMPLOT ACCIDENTALLY PLACED THE RAILCAR ON THE "SET-OUT" TRACK AND RELEASED IT FOR TRANSPORTATION PRIOR TO THE REPAIR.

column168: John Nein, Car Foreman, reported Tankcar DAX 7059 released product on a ballast surface at the east end of Track 302 in the Departure Yard in Cotton, CA. Mr. Nein advised the material was currently releasing approximately ten to fifteen drops every ten seconds Robert Bavier, Manager of Hazardous Material requested to be contacted by the shipper. At 07:35 PM, Don Morgan, Occidental Chemical, was conferenced with Mr. Bavier. At 10:10 PM, Bavier advised the material was releasing from the bottom outlet flange. Mr. Bavier further advised the material would be transloaded upon receipt of an empty tank car.

SELANDRAS VILLAUNEVA, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, ADVISED A CONDUCTOR REPORTED A STRONG CHEMICAL ODOR NEAR THE STRANG YARD IN LA PORTE, TX. TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. UPON INSPECTION OF TANK CAR TCIX 4307, MR. O'BRIEN FOUND THE GASKET OF THE QUICK FILL PORT OT BE MISSING. MR. O'BRIEN REPLACED THE GASKET AND RELEASED THE TANKCAR TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: Mark Wildman, Manager Terminal Operations, reported Tankcar NATX 24923 had an unusual odor around it at Bowl Five in the Englewood Yard, Houston, TX. Tim O'Brien, Regional Manager of Hazardous Material, was notified and responded. column168: KAREN HONEYCUTT, SUPERVISOR FORCES ENGINEERING, REPORTED A PROPANE SMELL EMITTING FROM THE BOWL NEAR THE OUTBOUND SERVICE AREA OF THE BAILEY RAILYARD IN NORTH PLATTE, NE. MS. HONEYCUTT STATED THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NOR HAD ANY EMPLOYEES REQUESTED MEDICAL ATTENTION. KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 05:54 PM, KEELING REPORTED HE WAS ON SITE AND RAILCAR NATX 37101 WAS RELEASING VAPOR FROM AN UNSECURED MANWAY. REQUESTED RMCC CONTACT THE SHIPPER. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND STATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE ALSO MADE. AT 08:24 PM, KIM KEELING REPORTED THE MANWAY GASKET HAD FAILED AND THE VACCUM RELIEF VALVE WAS ALSO BAD, CAUSING THE VAPOR TO RELEASE. THE VACCUM RELIEF VALVE WSA REMOVED AND WAS REPLACED WITH A PLUG. MR. KEELING ADVISED THAT A ONE TIME MOVEMENT APPORVAL WOULD BE REQUIRED TO MOVE THE CAR TO DESTINATION. MR. KEELING WAS CONFERRED WITH BARB KLETT, GLOBAL ETHANOL, TO ARRANGE FOR THE ONE TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL. MS. KLEET SECURED A MOVEMENT APPROVAL TO THE CAR TO BE MOVED TO DESTINATION AT GLOBAL ETHANOL IN LAKOTA IA.

Tim O'Brien, Regional Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. Upon inspcection of the tank car, Mr. O'Brien found the manway cover plate was not properly secured and a cup of liquid cresylic acid released on top of the tankcar. Mr. O'Brien secured the manway cover plate, cleaned the top of the car and released it to transportation.

John Matysiak, Manager of Train Operations, reported a release of product from the top of a Tankcar FXE 418018 located near Track 311 in the Settegast Railyard in Houston, TX. Tim O'Brien, Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. Upon inspection of the railcar, Mr. O'Brien found the frangible disc in the pressure relief device had been ruptured. Mr. O'Brien replaced the rupture disc with like kind. The top of the car was cleaned of residual acid and the car released to destination.

column168: AT 04:01 AM ON 8-17-07, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC, AND ADVISED THAT DAVID LARREAU, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, REPORTED PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR RCRX 1777 WITH NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED, OR REPORTED INJURIES. CAR WAS ISOLATED IN BOWL TRACK 26, AT THE LIVONIA, LA TRAIN YARD, MILE POST 114.20 OF THE LINONIA SUBDIVISION.    AFTER BEING NOTIFIED, MGR. LERCH REQUESTED THE RMCC MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION, AND WAS CONFERENCED WITH MR. JARREAU. MR. JARREAU ADVISED THE CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED, THE RELEASE WAS MINIMA, AND THE CAR WAS NO LONGER LEAKING.    MGR. LERCH THEN CONTACTED UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL, A UPRR CONTRACTOR, ADVISING THEM TO RESPOND TO THE SITE, MAKE REPAIRS, AND REMEDIATE THE AFFECTED AREA. AT APPROXIMATELY 04:45 AM, MGR. LERCH SPOKE TO SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE RAY BURNETT, RAIL MANAGEMENT MANAGER FOR REAGENT CHEMICAL RESEARCH, AND ADVISED HIM OF THE RELEASE AND ACTION TAKEN. MR. BURNETT REPORTED THAT HE WOULD DISPATCH PERSONNEL FROM THEIR ST. GABRIEL FACILITY WITH APPROPRIATE EQUIPMENT TO MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS, AND REMEDIATE THE AFFECTED AREA.    AT 07:25 AM, CHARLES SCHLATRE, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, ADVISED UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL HAD ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 07:15 AM AND INSPECTED THE TANK CAR NOTING RESIDUE PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE CAR.    AT 08:56 AM, REAGENT PERSONNEL AND UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL HAD REPLACED THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE AND NEUTRALIZED THE AFFECTED AREAS. TOTAL LOST PRODUCT WAS LESS THAN 1 GALLON, AND CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS UNDERTERMINED. UPON SECURING THE CAR, IT WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

At 08:59 AM, Smith advised Tankcar GATX 91294 was leaking a small amount of liquid onto the axle of the tankcar and a few drops were on the railties. Mr. Smith advised there was no odor or vapor and no injuries. Tankcar was located in Yard One, Track two and would be moved to the west end of the service track 506. Michael Moore, Manager of Hazardous Material, was notified and responded. Kenneth Machen, Lion Oil Company, Shipper, was conferenced with Mr. Moore and he advised he would contact GATX personnel to inspect the tankcar. Mr. Moore advised the release was not from a valve or manway, as they were all secured. He advised the release was from the B-end of tank itself, under the jacket. Moore also advised that tne shipper was transfering the product into trucks and the car would be sent to the GATX repair shop.

column58: Frangible Disc; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: At 1956hrs on 8-10-07, Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that Employee #1, Car Foreman, reported product leaking from the top of tank car FXE 418018. Car was located on the north end of track 308 Settegast Yard, Houston, TX. Check of waybill information indicated the car to be a residue empty last containing Sulfuric Acid, Class 8, Corrosive, UN1830. Upon being notified, Manager responded, and requested the RMCC make shipper notification via Chem-Trec.    Upon arrival and inspection of the car, Manager determined the car to be loaded, and noted a failed rupture disk within the safety vent assembly. Less than 1 gallon of product had been released with no impact to drains or waterways, and no reported injuries.    Upon replacement of the rupture disc, the affected areas were neutralized with a sodium bicarbonate solution. The car was then set out pending correct billing of the car. Cause of the release was due to hydraulic surge of the product while the car was being handled.    At 2047hrs, Employee #2, Plant Manager for Southern lonics, was contacted, advised of the release, incorrect billing, and corrective actions taken.    Employee #2, advised that he would have the billing corrected, and would have the car billed back to his facility for off loading and further handling of the car. On 8-24 car FXE 418018 arrived Southern lonics for off loading without further incident.    Cause of the incorrect billing was due to a miscommunication internally within Southern lonics. The car was inadvertently thought to have been off loaded, when it actually wasn t, and was then billed out as a residue empty.
column169: Assure good communication and documentation between off loading and billing personnel.
