column168: 8/15/07 — 07:3Oarn - San Diego: Southwest ramp personnel were unloading flight   139 from OAK. When ramp agent entered the “A” cargo Bin, he smelled a strong odor. After looking around, he noticed that there were 2 coolers that had turned over. The coolers were shipped by Lab Corp. Southwest airbill number: 90403876. The description of shipment on this airbill shows to be Biological Substance Category “B”. The leak appeared to come from these coolers but the agents were not 100% sure due to no noticeable evidence other than they were on their side. The smell seemed to be a formalin solution. It appeared that an undetermined amount of liquid had leaked out from one of these coolers and seemed to look more like condensation rather than a spill. After the bin was unloaded, the Pilot notified the Station Manager to call the 3E Company for information on the substance. The cargo freight agent (Edwin Borganic) was notified of the possible spill and he inspected the coolers. He stated that he could not tell that anything had spilled or leaked out of the coolers. Southwest Maintenance advised the ramp to clean the aircraft with Soap and water.

column168: Employee was entering a trailer with a pallet of paint. The pallet was not well balanced and not stretch-wrapped very well and not riding close to the ground. As the employee crossed over the dock plate, his load shifted and became unstable, causing the load to fall over into the trailer he was entering. Employee began to restack the cartons of paint onto another pallet when he noticed paint leaking out from underneath the pallet. Employee set to the side 5 cases covered with paint not knowing which carton was leaking. After he recouped the freight, we placed 5 cases of paint into salvage drums and are stored in LEP haz-mat trailer. Absorbal was used toaide in the cleanup of this spill.
column169: As in so many cases, freight companies continue to pick up freight from customers in which cartons/pails of paint are stacked too high and inadequately stretch-wrapped. A standard should require customers to stack 5-gallon pails to no more than 2 high on a pallet and cartons of paint stacked no-more than 4 high with adequate stretch-wrap.

Driver exited off of I-37 onto highway 181 going toward the Harbor bridge and took the ramp too fast turning his unit over onto its right side rupturing the cargo tank.  Fuel oil ran down the ramp in both directions and leaked onto the ground underneath through the drain holes in the ramp.  Miller Environmental was dispatched immediately to the scene and worked with the US Coast Guard and TX DOT to cover the drains before any product reached them.  No product got into any of the drains.  The entire area was remediated with the personnel of Miller Environmental under the direction of a company appointed representative from Garner Environmental.

column168: There was no package failure involved with this hazmat release. Minimal release was the result of a storage tank receiving design flaw due to an inadequate delivery hose tie-down. Product was being delivered by a delivery hose placed into the top of the storage tank. Pumping action caused the hose to jump and pull out of the top of the tank. 3-5 gallons of product was released onto the floor of the indoor storage area, before the driver was able to shut off the pump and stop the release, The consignee cleaned up the spill immediately.  The driver reported the spill at the time of the spill. This report was not filed within 30 days of the incident due to the incomplete understanding of the reporting requirements by the temporary supervisors on duty at the time. The incident occurred during a transition time after the departure of an experienced supervisor and before the hiring of a permanent replacement. (The temporary supervisors thought the reporting requirements for release were those applicable to spills greater than the reportable quantity (RQ), of which this quantity was less than the RQ.)  On 10-19-07, upon review by senior management, this release was determined to be reportable, although there was no package failure, due to the unintended nature of the release. This report is therefore being filed within 30 days of discovery that it is reportable as an unintended release.
column169: 1) We are working with the consignee to improve their process I equipment to ensure a secure hook-up of delivery hose to storage tank.  2) Refresher training for drivers and supervisors, primary and back-up, in reporting requirements completed week of October 22, 2007.  3) Sales, maintenance and driver personnel are being trained to recognize and address safe delivery concerns at customer locations. Our drivers are empowered to refuse to make a delivery if they feel it would create a spill or unsafe conditions.

column168: On 8/25/2007 at 2215, haz-mat response crew arrived at CRST terminal 924 S. Morgan Rd, Oklahoma City OK for a leaking 55g drum of printing ink. Upon opening the trailer doors, crew found 1 55g drum of black ink with a puncture hole at the bottom of the drum, apparently caused by a protruding shard of wood from the pallet in was on. This leaking drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon overpack drum. Upon unloading of trailer, 3 more leaking 5 gallon pails of white ink were discovered and overpacked into a 55g overpack drum. Speedy dry was used to absorb the spill of approximately 50 gallons of ink. A total of 3 55 gallon drums of ink impacted absorbent and debris, I 55g drum containing 3 5 gallon pails, and 1 85 gallon overpack containing the original 55g leaking drum was generated. Also 1 cubic yard of solid waste was generated. All of the waste drums were properly labeled and shipping tickets completed. All waste was properly disposed of at a certified waste disposal facility.

column168: Incident happened about 1:30pm on August 8, 2007. Our service driver was filling one of our customer’s above ground storage tanks with diesel fuel. Upon completion of the service work the driver shut off the valve and disconnected the hoses for storage. After removing the hose it was discovered that the valve was still releasing product and spilling onto the concrete parking lot.     Several attempts to close the valve failed, the driver called the operations manager who immediately left for the site. Driver collecting as much product in buckets as he could. Spill duration was probably several minutes. While in route to the site the operations manager called for support from their emergency response hazardous material company. While awaiting the arrival the hazmat company driver, operations manager and others built temporary dykes with sand.
column169: new company policy to check and verify valve.  when shutoff valve failed it was removed from equipment, inspected and set up as a training visual.  valves will be reconditioned or replaced at certain time intervals.

column168: The release occurred at 2321 S. Anderson Road, Rock Hill, S.C. The location is more appropriately known as the on ramp of SC SR 21 from SC SR 5. The cause of the release was a transportation incident involving a single vehicle rollover a Chemsolv owned and operated truck and semi trailer.    The incident occurred as the Chemsolv was entering South Anderson Road via a cloverleaf from SC SR 5. The truck may have been traveling too fast for conditions and toppled on to its side. The truck contained ten 330-gallon rigid poiy Intermediate Bulk Containers (US DOT 31IT11). Each container held 3,500 pounds of 75% Phosphoric Acid. Two containers breached and released 7,000 pounds of the solution. The material has a high viscosity and slowly migrated across the road to gravel/turf shoulder.

column168: BASED ON INFORMATION SUPPLIED BY MR. ARRINGTON WITH DOT, WE BELIEVE THE FOLLOWING MAY HAVE OCCURRED:  A SMALL "CATCH PAN" IS MOUNTED ON THE REAR FRAME OF OUR GASOLINE/DIESEL DELIVERY STRAIGHT TRUCKS.  THE PAN HAS AN APPROXIMATELY VOLUME OF 2 GALLONS.  THE CATCH PAN IS DESIGNED TO CAPTURE THE SMALL AMOUNT OF FUEL THAT IS RELEASED AS A HOSE IS DISCONNECTED FROM ONE OF THE COUPLINGS.  THE CATCH PAIN IS EQUIPPED WITH A VALUE, TO BE USED TO EMPTY THE PAN INTO A BUCKET FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  BASED ON THE "DISCHARGED IN SEVERAL LOCATIONS" COMMENT BY DOT, IF THE CATCH PAN IS NOT EMPTIED, IT IS REASONABLE THAT, AS THE DRIVER ACCELERATES AND MAKES A SHARP TURN ONTO THE HIGHWAY, SOME FUEL MAY "SLOSH" OUT.  THE RELEASE WOULD HAVE BEEN LESS THAN 2 GALLONS, WHICH WOULD HAVE EVAPORATED ON THE ASPHALT HIGHWAY AND WOULD NOT HAVE CAUSED ANY ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE.  OUR DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED ON THE PROPER PROCEDURE (EMPTYING THE FUEL FROM THE CATCH PAN INTO A BUCKET).

column168: OUTER PACKAGE BROKE OPEN AND AEROSOL CANS DISCOVERED. REPORTED TO JOE BALLAS WITH THE FAA ON 9/29/07 AT 11:15 AM. SENT ELECTRONIC COPY OF THE INCIDENT REPORT.

8/1 6/07 — Southwest ramp personnel were loading this Customers bag and noticed the bag was wet. After opening the bag, our ramp agents found a container that had spilled about 16 fluid ounces of liquid. The material was Lysol Brand Disinfectant Mildew Remover with Bleach (UN3266, Corrosive liquid, basic, inorganic, n.o.s.(Sodium Hydroxide, Sodium Hypoclorite) class 8, PG III — Limited Quantity). The MSDS shows that item has been reclassified as a Consumer Commodity, ORM-D.  The container was removed and looked to have a cracked lid. The container was removed, double bagged and held or inspection. The outside of the Customers bag was then cleaned washed, double bagged and loaded onto the aircraft for shipment to Orlando (MCO). There was another bag adjacent to the one that contained the spill. That bag had a very small amount spilled on it also. That bag was also checked, washed down and loaded. The Customer was advised that the item was leaking and removed. An electronic HazMat discrepancy report (lR7391), was also submitted to the regional FAA HazMat office. TSA was also notified and was asked why the item was not removed from the Customers bag. TSA’s response was that the item did not alarm.
